metadata.name: the centre cannot hold #159
metadata.description:
The spiral is one of the earliest symbols used by humans, found in cave paintings and petroglyphs, and is thought by some researchers to have been inspired by shamanic rituals and hallucinogenic experiences. 

The spiral is found in our mathematics via the golden ratio, and in our aesthetics via the Fibonacci Spiral, aka the Golden Spiral. Spirals are found throughout the natural world, from the shape of our galaxy, to hurricane storms in our atmosphere, to seashells in the oceans.   

Spirals are also used to conceptualize entropy, spiraling out of control, the downward spiral from order into chaos. Each of these works represents this form of spiral, with varying degrees of chaos versus order, a formerly-cohesive group throwing off parts of itself due to overwhelming centrifugal force.   
--  
Uses p5js (LGPL-2.1). Color palettes are inspired by the paintings of Mondrian, Rafael, Van Gogh, Munch, O'Keefe, and Magritte.

Coded Tiny Dinos.

metadata.name: BLEND #172
metadata.description:
Blend are generative loops and animated pieces creating a shape with a digital painting effect.
The size, position and motion frequency of trails are generated for each token, along with the color theme. 
You can press spacebar to stop the animation.

Created by Quentin Hocd√©, in Brussels (Belgium).‚Ä®‚Ä®

Features :
	- Between 10 and 80 trails, impacted or not by an update of their radius and randomly filled
	- 4 directions - from North West (NW), from North East (NE), from North or from West.
	- Duration between 16 and 24 seconds
	- Amplitude of the shape on X and Y
	- Offset delay: between 0.1 and trails count, manage the delay between each trails movement
	- Noise count : number of points to create the noise effect on background
	- Background color :  color randomly get from 1 of 151 color themes

metadata.name: Glomularus #158
metadata.description:
Glomularus is an exploration in generative, artificial life forms. The project is an extension of my Protobyte series, begun in 2004.

Driven by Verlet icosahedra and responsive tendrils, Glomulari live in a spherical virtual ecosystem (V-eco) enhanced through user interaction.

Interaction:

Mouse/Trackpad:
  drag -> camera rotation
  drag + CMD/CTR -> camera pan
  scroll wheel/pinch -> camera zoom

Key Input:
  1-9: add acceleration
  -, +: reduce | increase V-eco sphere radius
  f, g: reduce | increase fog
  p: screen capture

Tip:
To decrease creature acceleration, reduce V-eco sphere radius

Note:
Please post your favorite Glomularus screen captures
TW: @iragreenberg
IG: @greenberg.ira

Built with Three.js, PByte.js, TypeScript, Node

metadata.name: RGB Elementary Cellular Automaton #780
metadata.description:
Stephen Wolfram's Elementary Cellular Automaton where 3 different rules are drawn in the Red, Green and Blue color components of the image.

Rules are selected randomly among a pre-selection of 53 rules from which nice behaviors emerge.

Tokens can have a cell size in the [1; 20] range.

metadata.name: LineColorComposition2 #39
metadata.description:
Our story: In 1973 I was an instructor of Engineering Graphics in the College of Engineering at Michigan State University as well as a graduate student in Graphic Design. In the College of Engineering I was fortunate enough to meet Christopher Scussel, a fellow graduate student who was majoring in a new program called Computer Science. I was struggling using the earliest forms of computer equipment and the cumbersome programming language called FORTRAN to make make computer art. I asked Chris for help and he graciously consented. That began our amazing friendship that has lasted to this day.

Chris and I collaborated on a number of early pieces. He showed me how to formulate algorithms into code. He showed me how to program the primitive equipment of the time: line printers, storage scopes and pen plotters to make graphic output. We even built our own graphic output device, an 8 x 8 array of light bulbs. We were indeed pioneers.

Chris graduated in 1976 and has since retired after working 37 years as a research scientist at Bell Labs. I went on to get a Ph.D in 1981 and moved on with my life (see my story on (www.drbillkolomyjec.com). I started making generative art again in 2020. In true "glory days" spirit I tracked Chris down to see if he was interested in collaborating. Once again he graciously consented citing an opportunity for "creative stimulation", so here we go again. It is pure joy to be working with Chris again. 

This encore work represents the second "published" output of our renewed collaboration. Beyond the contiguous lines that do not cross in LineColorComposition1, in LineColorComposition2 a grid or mesh of lines affected by the same vector field algorithm. The images produced have the same look of voluptuous, organic quality visual landscapes but the feel is different because of the crossing lines. We hope you enjoy this variation of Chris' unique algorithm. Again, I added a few subtle tweaks.

Check out Dr. Bill Generative Art OG @ drbillkolomyjec.com

metadata.name: Dencity #556
metadata.description:
Dencity is a generative art project inspired by aerial views of cities with a high density of buildings. Its perspective effect, its perfectly imprecise lines, its subtle textures and its very advanced level of detail give it the appearance of a hand-drawn work.

Behind the visible art (the image) hides another form of art, an extremely complex algorithm capable of calculating and drawing in 2D each variation of the Dencity project. To draw a variation, the algorithm notably takes around 3,000,000 to 20,000,000 random decisions based on the hash of the mint and draws around 800,000 to 4,000,000 lines to create all the strokes and texture effects.

Made with ‚ù§Ô∏è, code and p5js.

metadata.name: Miniscapes #300
metadata.description:
Miniscapes merges generative code (Rich's bit) with meticulously designed scenes and elements (Rick's bit), to create minimalist landscapes intended to charm, delight, and surprise.

Our aim was to convey as much as possible with as little as possible by using simple shapes and lines to represent a wide variety of natural landscapes.

We hope that you find as much joy in owning a Miniscape as we did in creating them.

Controls (in live view):
- Press [s] to save the current image
- Press [p] to pause an animated output
- Press [r] to reset an animated output (this will also pause)

metadata.name: Traversal #58
metadata.description:
Traversal is the marriage of two simple geometric ideas: a set of somewhat unruly, intersecting diagonal shapes, and a minimally reduced corner perspective that gives them depth.

The depicted bodies are entirely feasible as a 3D scene, and yet this composition is all about illusion. The hatch fill creates a perception of light. The dithering on the faces produces a sense of material texture. The squiggly lines imitate freehand drawing. The spatial perspective itself is achieved through a purely two-dimensional algorithm of polygon intersections and line hiding.

The original medium of my compositions is the pen plotter, and Traversal is no exception. It is entirely vector-based, and can be plotted directly. I use Paper.js to render it on-screen and as SVG.

~

To generate and download a plottable SVG file, press `S`. Please be patient; this process can take a while. The SVG can be plotted on an A5 paper. It contains two layers visible in Inkscape, so you can plot the light grey sketch lines with a different pen, or omit them altogether.
